# Code of Business Conduct and Ethics

Produce a board-ready Code of Business Conduct and Ethics tailored to the company’s operations and U.S. public-company compliance obligations.

## Prerequisites

1. Company legal name, jurisdiction of incorporation, ownership status, and exchange (if any)
2. Existing governance docs and policies to align or supersede
3. Industry regulatory obligations and jurisdictions of operation
4. Reporting channels and contact points (hotline, Legal, Compliance, Audit Committee)
5. Disciplinary authority and waiver approval body

## Output Structure / Process

Draft in the following order and include every required section.

**Drafting Checklist**
1. Confirm scope and covered persons
2. Insert tone-from-the-top leadership statement
3. Map required topics (SOX 406, listing standards) to sections
4. Tailor conflicts, gifts, and industry risks with examples
5. Define reporting, investigations, anti-retaliation, and enforcement
6. Define waiver process and disclosure requirements
7. Add acknowledgment and version/effective date

**Required Sections Table**

| Section | Purpose | Required Content |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Title + Effective Date | Anchors the document | Full legal name; version; effective date |
| Leadership Statement | Tone from the top | Commitment to ethics and compliance; shared responsibility |
| Scope + Applicability | Covered persons | Employees, officers, directors, senior financial officers; affiliates/contractors if applicable |
| Relationship to Other Policies | Hierarchy | Cross-reference policies; “most stringent applies” rule |
| Legal Compliance | Baseline standard | Compliance with laws/regulations; seek guidance when unclear |
| SOX 406 Code of Ethics | Public-company requirement | Honest and ethical conduct; conflicts; full, fair, accurate, timely disclosure; compliance with laws; internal reporting; accountability |
| Conflicts of Interest | Define + manage conflicts | Definition; disclosure duty; approval process; examples |
| Corporate Opportunities | Prevent usurpation | Definition; no personal benefit without approval |
| Confidentiality + Data | Protect information | Scope; third-party info; security practices; post-employment duty; lawful carve-outs |
| Company Assets | Protect property | Proper use; limited personal use rules; report misuse |
| Fair Dealing | Competitive integrity | No manipulation, concealment, misrepresentation, or abuse |
| Reporting + Investigations | Safe reporting | Multiple channels; confidentiality limits; cooperate |
| Non-Retaliation | Whistleblower protection | Prohibit retaliation; report retaliation process |
| Enforcement | Accountability | Disciplinary range; failure-to-report liability |
| Waivers | Board oversight | Board or committee approval for execs/directors; disclosure obligations |
| Acknowledgment | Evidence of receipt | Signature block; annual or onboarding execution |

**Section Templates**

```text
Leadership Statement (from CEO/Chair)
- Ethics and compliance are essential to our success.
- This Code guides decisions when rules are unclear.
- Every covered person shares responsibility.

Scope
- Applies to all employees, officers, and directors.
- Includes senior financial officers as defined by SEC rules.
- [Optional] Applies to contractors and agents acting on our behalf.

Conflicts of Interest
- A conflict exists when personal interests interfere or appear to interfere with company interests.
- Disclose promptly to [Compliance Officer/Legal].
- No activity may proceed without written approval.

Reporting
- Report concerns to: supervisor, HR, Legal, Compliance, Ethics Hotline, Audit Committee (for accounting/audit).
- Anonymous reporting: [Yes/No].
- All reports are investigated; confidentiality maintained to the extent feasible.

Non-Retaliation
- Good-faith reporting or participation in investigations is protected.
- Retaliation is grounds for дисциплиline up to termination.

Waivers
- Only the Board or designated committee may grant waivers for executive officers or directors.
- Any such waiver will be disclosed as required by law and listing standards.
```

**Industry Add-On Table (Include if applicable)**

| Industry | Add-On Topics |
| --- | --- |
| Financial Services | Insider trading, fiduciary duties, customer privacy |
| Healthcare | Anti-kickback, patient privacy, research integrity |
| Government Contracting | Procurement integrity, cost accounting, security |
| Tech/Data | Data governance, AI ethics, cybersecurity |
| Environmental Impact | Environmental compliance, sustainability commitments |

**Acknowledgment Block (Add to end)**

```text
I acknowledge receipt of the Code of Business Conduct and Ethics, understand its contents, and agree to comply.
Name:
Title:
Signature:
Date:
```

## Guidelines

- U.S. focus: align with SEC SOX 406 code-of-ethics requirements and applicable exchange listing standards.
- Use concrete examples tied to actual business activities; avoid hypothetical edge cases.
- Include lawful whistleblower and government-cooperation carve-outs; do not waive statutory rights.
- Avoid employment promises or “cause” language unless approved by HR/Legal.
- If multiple jurisdictions apply, add a short “Local Law Conflicts” provision and require Legal review.
- Mark any uncertain legal citations with `[VERIFY]`.
